1
00:00:17,463 --> 00:00:19,754
[♪ dramatic music playing]

2
00:00:19,755 --> 00:00:23,130
Hey, I like to think that I...
We have evolved.

3
00:00:23,422 --> 00:00:24,546
[gun clicks]

4
00:00:24,547 --> 00:00:25,797
[gunshot]

5
00:00:26,547 --> 00:00:29,004
- [Karen] Foggy!
- Why? Why?

6
00:00:29,005 --> 00:00:31,212
- [grunts]
- [thuds]

7
00:00:31,213 --> 00:00:32,337
[breathing heavily]

8
00:00:32,338 --> 00:00:33,922
[Karen] <i>What're you gonna do
about Daredevil?</i>

9
00:00:34,588 --> 00:00:35,921
[Matt] <i>I'm not him anymore.</i>

10
00:00:35,922 --> 00:00:39,546
<i>I made a promise to myself
that I'd let the system handle it.</i>

11
00:00:39,547 --> 00:00:41,130
Take care of yourself, Matt.

12
00:00:42,672 --> 00:00:44,254
It's been some time, hasn't it?

13
00:00:44,255 --> 00:00:46,462
I was wondering
if we could have a little chat?

14
00:00:46,463 --> 00:00:48,879
So if you step out of line,
I will be there.

15
00:00:48,880 --> 00:00:52,379
Should you go back
to any of your old activities,

16
00:00:52,380 --> 00:00:54,421
there will be consequences.

17
00:00:54,422 --> 00:00:56,421
[reporter on TV]
<i>Wilson Fisk has been elected</i>

18
00:00:56,422 --> 00:00:58,462
<i>the 112th mayor of New York City.</i>

19
00:00:58,463 --> 00:00:59,547
He won.

20
00:01:02,797 --> 00:01:04,838
[♪ suspenseful music playing]

21
00:01:08,630 --> 00:01:10,338
[woman] Sir, let me
touch up your eye.

22
00:01:10,922 --> 00:01:11,922
[woman sighs]

23
00:01:14,922 --> 00:01:16,255
[objects clattering]

24
00:01:17,630 --> 00:01:18,922
[Fisk exhales]

25
00:01:19,838 --> 00:01:21,838
[♪ dramatic music intensifies]

26
00:01:25,130 --> 00:01:27,005
[♪ tense music playing]

27
00:01:29,713 --> 00:01:31,047
Thank you, New York.

28
00:01:32,422 --> 00:01:35,004
Vanessa and I,
we offer our deepest regards.

29
00:01:35,005 --> 00:01:36,087
[crowd cheering]

30
00:01:36,088 --> 00:01:39,962
<i>It's humbling to be sitting here,
speaking to you as mayor this evening.</i>

31
00:01:39,963 --> 00:01:42,171
- [crowd booing]
<i>- Beginning of the new year,</i>

32
00:01:42,172 --> 00:01:45,754
<i>and most importantly, a new era
for the greatest city in the world.</i>

33
00:01:45,755 --> 00:01:47,004
[all cheering]

34
00:01:47,005 --> 00:01:51,921
[Fisk] <i>This city is in shambles.
Crime, poverty, a feeling of uneasiness,</i>

35
00:01:51,922 --> 00:01:55,338
{\an8}<i>as if any moment, things could explode.</i>

36
00:01:56,088 --> 00:01:59,296
{\an8}<i>But New Yorkers are tough.
We know how to take care of ourselves.</i>

37
00:01:59,297 --> 00:02:02,921
<i>We don't need a gun-toting vigilante
who wears a skull on his chest</i>

38
00:02:02,922 --> 00:02:06,587
<i>or a man who dresses in a spider outfit.</i>

39
00:02:06,588 --> 00:02:09,712
<i>Or a guy who wears devil horns
to save us. No.</i>

40
00:02:09,713 --> 00:02:11,505
- [siren blaring in distance]
<i>- We'll be our best once again.</i>

41
00:02:12,880 --> 00:02:14,004
[woman echoing] Fisk, the mayor?

42
00:02:14,005 --> 00:02:16,004
- I-- I just can't.
- [Fisk] <i>I made you one promise.</i>

43
00:02:16,005 --> 00:02:18,879
[man 1] What are you gonna do,
move to Boston? You hate the Celtics.

44
00:02:18,880 --> 00:02:20,629
- [Fisk] <i>I intend to keep it.</i>
- [man 2] You hearing this guy?

45
00:02:20,630 --> 00:02:22,588
[man 3] Hear him? I fucking love him.

46
00:02:23,213 --> 00:02:24,837
[Fisk] <i>And that is that the rule of law</i>

47
00:02:24,838 --> 00:02:27,047
<i>- will return to New York City.
-</i> [crowd cheering]

48
00:02:27,880 --> 00:02:30,797
[Fisk] <i>That is what I will deliver
to the city of New York.</i>

49
00:02:31,630 --> 00:02:35,962
<i>The city that bore me, elected me.
The city that I love.</i>

50
00:02:35,963 --> 00:02:37,046
[siren blaring]

51
00:02:37,047 --> 00:02:40,129
<i>Good night and happy new year.</i>

52
00:02:40,130 --> 00:02:42,922
[man 1 speaking Spanish] <i>Es que ya yo
te dije donde yo estaba.</i>

53
00:02:43,588 --> 00:02:46,047
<i>Tenía unas cuantas cositas
que hacer y se me fue el tiempo.</i>

54
00:02:47,505 --> 00:02:49,379
- [man 2 in English] No, no.
- [man 3] You don't got nothing on you.

55
00:02:49,380 --> 00:02:50,587
[man 2] I got-- Nothing, nothing.

56
00:02:50,588 --> 00:02:51,671
[man 3] What are you doing, Nicky?

57
00:02:51,672 --> 00:02:53,337
- You trying to dodge us?
- [in Spanish] <i>Me tengo que ir.</i>

58
00:02:53,338 --> 00:02:55,629
[Nicky in English] I wasn't dodging you,
man. I've just been, you know, busy.

59
00:02:55,630 --> 00:02:57,421
- [man 4] I think you've been dodging us.
- No, no, no, man.

60
00:02:57,422 --> 00:02:58,587
Just doing my own thing.

61
00:02:58,588 --> 00:03:00,546
- [in English] Hey.
- [man 3] It seems like you are.

62
00:03:00,547 --> 00:03:02,172
- [Nicky] Hey, hey.
- [punches]

63
00:03:02,672 --> 00:03:05,088
- Hey! Take it easy!
- [Nicky] I don't have anything.

64
00:03:05,922 --> 00:03:07,796
Hey, buddy, this doesn't concern you.

65
00:03:07,797 --> 00:03:10,296
Hey! You're beatin' on a guy
who can't defend himself.

66
00:03:10,297 --> 00:03:12,046
- It concerns me.
- Okay, okay.

67
00:03:12,047 --> 00:03:13,130
I said stay out of it.

68
00:03:13,838 --> 00:03:16,255
[both grunting]

69
00:03:17,213 --> 00:03:18,421
[struggling]

70
00:03:18,422 --> 00:03:19,504
Let it go.

71
00:03:19,505 --> 00:03:20,629
[Nicky grunts]

72
00:03:20,630 --> 00:03:22,297
[both grunting]

73
00:03:23,255 --> 00:03:24,255
[man 4] Hey!

74
00:03:24,838 --> 00:03:25,838
No.

75
00:03:26,172 --> 00:03:27,380
- [man 1 grunts]
- [groans]

76
00:03:29,130 --> 00:03:30,921
[♪ tense music playing]

77
00:03:30,922 --> 00:03:32,380
- [grunts]
- [groans]

78
00:03:33,047 --> 00:03:34,588
- [growls]
- [groans]

79
00:03:35,380 --> 00:03:36,379
[groaning]

80
00:03:36,380 --> 00:03:38,380
[both grunting]

81
00:03:40,963 --> 00:03:42,504
- [grunts loudly]
- [man 4] No! [screams]

82
00:03:42,505 --> 00:03:44,130
[train screeching]

83
00:03:52,297 --> 00:03:54,713
NYPD. Do not move.

84
00:03:58,630 --> 00:04:00,672
[♪ dramatic music playing]

85
00:04:04,672 --> 00:04:06,672
[♪ theme music playing]

86
00:05:44,213 --> 00:05:46,172
[BB] <i>Any thoughts on the disappearance
of Daredevil?</i>

87
00:05:48,297 --> 00:05:51,380
{\an8}[man] <i>Daredevil?</i> [chuckling] <i>Haven't heard
that name in a long time, man.</i>

88
00:05:52,338 --> 00:05:54,087
{\an8}And I don't miss him. He's a clown.

89
00:05:54,088 --> 00:05:57,255
{\an8}<i>You know, who needs him? He's more trouble
than he's worth. Good riddance.</i>

90
00:05:57,838 --> 00:05:59,879
{\an8}Are the strong obligated
to protect the weak?

91
00:05:59,880 --> 00:06:01,796
{\an8}Yeah, they are,
but they're kind of whiny about it.

92
00:06:01,797 --> 00:06:04,337
{\an8}<i>And then they start
preying on the weak.</i>

93
00:06:04,338 --> 00:06:09,380
Fire Chief Carter is your 10 a.m.
We can do that here or at the firehouse.

94
00:06:09,963 --> 00:06:14,379
Firehouse. Carter,
he's known to be a doubter,

95
00:06:14,380 --> 00:06:16,004
so best I come to him.

96
00:06:16,005 --> 00:06:19,129
My thoughts exactly.
After that, we have six more stops.

97
00:06:19,130 --> 00:06:23,588
I've put in another call
to Commissioner Gallo. It's our third.

98
00:06:25,880 --> 00:06:27,838
How old do you think this desk is?

99
00:06:29,130 --> 00:06:30,755
- [fingers tapping]
- Excuse me?

100
00:06:31,797 --> 00:06:35,338
How long do you think this desk
has been here? It's old.

101
00:06:37,130 --> 00:06:38,504
Vanessa would know by sight.

102
00:06:38,505 --> 00:06:40,672
[♪ menacing music playing]

103
00:06:41,713 --> 00:06:45,005
You wonder.
Did Fiorello La Guardia sit here?

104
00:06:45,963 --> 00:06:49,422
He was a hero of my father's, you know?

105
00:06:50,380 --> 00:06:51,755
No, no, I didn't.

106
00:06:59,588 --> 00:07:01,713
My father, he didn't respect many men.

107
00:07:02,255 --> 00:07:04,005
Well, none actually.

108
00:07:06,172 --> 00:07:08,130
Except for La Guardia.

109
00:07:11,130 --> 00:07:15,172
His tenacity.
Him standing up to Tammany Hall.

110
00:07:16,463 --> 00:07:19,005
Fiorello La Guardia, he built this city.

111
00:07:22,755 --> 00:07:24,046
[inhales sharply]

112
00:07:24,047 --> 00:07:25,504
Sir...

113
00:07:25,505 --> 00:07:27,254
Yeah, I-- Sorry. Yes.

114
00:07:27,255 --> 00:07:28,338
Uh...

115
00:07:30,630 --> 00:07:31,797
[sighs wearily]

116
00:07:32,588 --> 00:07:38,755
I'm really looking forward to meeting
District Attorney Hochberg.

117
00:07:40,047 --> 00:07:43,505
These meet and greets, can't we push them?

118
00:07:44,630 --> 00:07:49,004
These first few days are critical.
Optics are gonna matter.

119
00:07:49,005 --> 00:07:52,504
Establishing connections is how we set
the tone with the stakeholders

120
00:07:52,505 --> 00:07:55,004
who can make or break your agenda.

121
00:07:55,005 --> 00:07:58,630
And let's be honest, a lot
of these people absolutely hate you.

122
00:08:01,422 --> 00:08:03,838
[laughs]

123
00:08:06,838 --> 00:08:08,713
- I'm used to that.
- [Sheila chuckles]

124
00:08:09,922 --> 00:08:12,547
And there's something else.

125
00:08:13,713 --> 00:08:19,838
And I'm sorry if this is heading
into personal territory. Your wife...

126
00:08:21,838 --> 00:08:22,922
What about Vanessa?

127
00:08:25,422 --> 00:08:30,796
Uh, okay. Well, the inaugural speech
tracked better than expected,

128
00:08:30,797 --> 00:08:33,047
especially with the younger constituents.

129
00:08:34,422 --> 00:08:39,837
However, Vanessa's resistance
to being part of the narrative

130
00:08:39,838 --> 00:08:43,004
is hurting you
with more traditional voters.

131
00:08:43,005 --> 00:08:44,297
[inhales deeply]

132
00:08:45,463 --> 00:08:46,463
I see.

133
00:08:49,713 --> 00:08:51,713
[♪ somber music playing]

134
00:08:54,505 --> 00:08:55,963
[Fisk sighs]

135
00:08:56,797 --> 00:09:00,255
Uh, the timing on this is not ideal,

136
00:09:00,838 --> 00:09:06,005
but my wife and I, we have work to do.

137
00:09:07,713 --> 00:09:10,963
Could you grant us a little leeway?

138
00:09:12,463 --> 00:09:14,172
Absolutely, sir.

139
00:09:18,380 --> 00:09:19,630
[door opens]

140
00:09:20,797 --> 00:09:21,880
[door closes]

141
00:09:27,672 --> 00:09:29,087
[sirens blaring]

142
00:09:29,088 --> 00:09:31,504
[Matt] Well, the good news is
she's in holding. She's sobering up

143
00:09:31,505 --> 00:09:34,504
and back amongst the living.
I also wouldn't hold my breath.

144
00:09:34,505 --> 00:09:37,546
Her blood alcohol was 0.15
and she has two priors, so...

145
00:09:37,547 --> 00:09:39,254
Do you have any idea
of how long this will take?

146
00:09:39,255 --> 00:09:41,004
- [metal clanking]
- Because I was hoping to get to work

147
00:09:41,005 --> 00:09:42,837
- and I can't miss another shift.
- [punch blows]

148
00:09:42,838 --> 00:09:44,504
[officer] Now here's what's gonna happen,
cop killer.

149
00:09:44,505 --> 00:09:46,462
- [punch blows]
- [man groans]

150
00:09:46,463 --> 00:09:48,254
[officer] You are gonna sign a confession.

151
00:09:48,255 --> 00:09:50,254
- [man groans]
- [Matt] You know what? I--

152
00:09:50,255 --> 00:09:52,129
I told a colleague
I'd check on a client of theirs.

153
00:09:52,130 --> 00:09:54,796
Let me do that. Um, I'll call you later
if I have an update, okay?

154
00:09:54,797 --> 00:09:56,671
- [woman] Okay.
- Thank you.

155
00:09:56,672 --> 00:09:58,087
[♪ stirring music playing]

156
00:09:58,088 --> 00:10:00,255
[man groans]

157
00:10:01,797 --> 00:10:03,755
[indistinct conversation]

158
00:10:07,213 --> 00:10:08,213
[Matt] Thank you.

159
00:10:09,505 --> 00:10:11,422
- [door lock beeps]
- [handcuffs clanking]

160
00:10:12,047 --> 00:10:13,130
[door closes]

161
00:10:14,297 --> 00:10:15,297
Hector Ayala?

162
00:10:15,422 --> 00:10:17,338
[♪ stirring music continues]

163
00:10:20,838 --> 00:10:21,880
Those guys tune you up?

164
00:10:23,963 --> 00:10:25,588
- Does it matter?
- [Matt chuckles] Yeah.

165
00:10:26,588 --> 00:10:28,047
It does. Matters to me.

166
00:10:29,130 --> 00:10:31,379
I'm a lawyer. My name is Matthew.

167
00:10:31,380 --> 00:10:32,712
You're the public defender?

168
00:10:32,713 --> 00:10:34,962
No. I'm a defense attorney.
I have my own practice.

169
00:10:34,963 --> 00:10:36,629
I didn't call you.
How'd you get in here?

170
00:10:36,630 --> 00:10:38,588
You know, they're saying you killed a cop?

171
00:10:39,088 --> 00:10:41,422
All I was trying to do was help a guy out.

172
00:10:42,088 --> 00:10:43,547
Well, that's not their story.

173
00:10:44,505 --> 00:10:47,087
They're saying you approached
two officers on the platform--

174
00:10:47,088 --> 00:10:50,672
No, man. <i>Esos hijos de puta</i>
on the platform never said they were cops.

175
00:10:51,380 --> 00:10:52,504
They never said nothing.

176
00:10:52,505 --> 00:10:55,130
Look, all I was trying to do
was break up a beating, okay?

177
00:10:55,672 --> 00:10:57,046
So what happened to the officer who--

178
00:10:57,047 --> 00:10:58,962
One of them tripped trying to take me out.

179
00:10:58,963 --> 00:11:00,796
Look, I didn't push him, I swear.

180
00:11:00,797 --> 00:11:02,879
I wasn't trying to kill anybody.
That's not me.

181
00:11:02,880 --> 00:11:04,962
[echoing] And I sure as shit
didn't know

182
00:11:04,963 --> 00:11:06,047
there was a train coming.

183
00:11:06,547 --> 00:11:08,421
- [heart beating]
- I mean, one second he's there,

184
00:11:08,422 --> 00:11:10,255
and then... he's gone.

185
00:11:10,797 --> 00:11:13,921
- [heart thumping]
- [train screeching]

186
00:11:13,922 --> 00:11:15,004
[groans]

187
00:11:15,005 --> 00:11:16,963
Is there anything you're not telling me?

188
00:11:19,005 --> 00:11:20,296
[handcuffs rattling]

189
00:11:20,297 --> 00:11:22,547
- [Hector, echoing] No, man. Nothing.
- [heartbeat thumping]

190
00:11:23,797 --> 00:11:25,546
- [thumping stops]
- [groans softly]

191
00:11:25,547 --> 00:11:26,712
[breathes heavily]

192
00:11:26,713 --> 00:11:29,797
You're still pretty wired, I'm sure.
Everything is a little fuzzy.

193
00:11:30,630 --> 00:11:31,879
We need to go over it
a few more times

194
00:11:31,880 --> 00:11:32,962
before the arraignment.

195
00:11:32,963 --> 00:11:35,379
- But for now, that's all we need to do.
- I can't afford you.

196
00:11:35,380 --> 00:11:38,004
Don't worry about that.
I'd still like to represent you.

197
00:11:38,005 --> 00:11:39,922
[footsteps receding]

198
00:11:41,213 --> 00:11:42,505
You're in good hands, Hector.

199
00:11:43,213 --> 00:11:44,213
Wait, hold up.

200
00:11:45,838 --> 00:11:46,838
You're blind?

201
00:11:48,130 --> 00:11:49,713
[chuckles softly]

202
00:11:50,713 --> 00:11:52,172
[door opens]

203
00:11:53,088 --> 00:11:54,379
[door closes]

204
00:11:54,380 --> 00:11:56,296
[cars honking]

205
00:11:56,297 --> 00:11:57,379
[woman] Shut up!

206
00:11:57,380 --> 00:11:58,505
[indistinct chatter]

207
00:11:59,338 --> 00:12:01,921
Once we arrive at the senior center,
you'll say a few words,

208
00:12:01,922 --> 00:12:04,921
and then they want to present you
with the key to the borough.

209
00:12:04,922 --> 00:12:07,379
I'm already the mayor.
Why do I need a key to Brooklyn?

210
00:12:07,380 --> 00:12:09,962
Like it or not,
the outer boroughs are your base.

211
00:12:09,963 --> 00:12:11,212
Especially Staten Island.

212
00:12:11,213 --> 00:12:13,380
You got Staten, don't need Manhattan.

213
00:12:13,922 --> 00:12:15,837
- [horns honking]
- Sorry.

214
00:12:15,838 --> 00:12:19,046
This city is broken. I said I'd fix it.

215
00:12:19,047 --> 00:12:21,087
[Sheila] Sir, the first 100 days
are about settling in,

216
00:12:21,088 --> 00:12:22,963
getting a feel for the office.

217
00:12:23,547 --> 00:12:26,337
Try anything big now,
you're painting a target on your back.

218
00:12:26,338 --> 00:12:29,005
Good. Targets draw attention to problems.

219
00:12:29,838 --> 00:12:31,504
[Sheila] You hired me because I know

220
00:12:31,505 --> 00:12:33,837
- how politics work in New York City...
- [Fisk sighs]

221
00:12:33,838 --> 00:12:37,462
...and right now, it's all about
maintaining the status quo.

222
00:12:37,463 --> 00:12:40,462
So your advice to the newly
inaugurated mayor of New York

223
00:12:40,463 --> 00:12:42,629
- is that he do nothing.
- [honking increases]

224
00:12:42,630 --> 00:12:43,796
What's going on here?

225
00:12:43,797 --> 00:12:45,087
It's a big hole.

226
00:12:45,088 --> 00:12:46,712
We'll be around it in, like, a minute.

227
00:12:46,713 --> 00:12:48,672
[honking continues]

228
00:12:50,963 --> 00:12:52,337
[man] Hey. Hey, what're you doing?

229
00:12:52,338 --> 00:12:53,505
[seat belt clicks]

230
00:12:54,588 --> 00:12:57,671
Oh... Sir, I'd advise against
whatever you--

231
00:12:57,672 --> 00:12:59,671
- Shit. Why didn't you stop him?
- [honking continues]

232
00:12:59,672 --> 00:13:02,047
That's your job, not mine.

233
00:13:04,172 --> 00:13:06,337
[Fisk] Foreman. Who's the foreman?

234
00:13:06,338 --> 00:13:09,588
[foreman] Yeah. What's up?
Hey, you're the mayor.

235
00:13:10,213 --> 00:13:11,504
- [Fisk] Yes.
- How you doing?

236
00:13:11,505 --> 00:13:14,171
I want you to stop what you're doing
and fill that hole.

237
00:13:14,172 --> 00:13:16,629
You have the equipment
and the manpower.

238
00:13:16,630 --> 00:13:18,462
[foreman] Hey, sorry, sir.
It's the red tape.

239
00:13:18,463 --> 00:13:20,379
We're waitin' on the permit approval.

240
00:13:20,380 --> 00:13:21,962
[Fisk] Consider it approved.

241
00:13:21,963 --> 00:13:24,421
You got it. Fellas, hole!

242
00:13:24,422 --> 00:13:27,004
Let's go. Now! Move!

243
00:13:27,005 --> 00:13:28,587
- [worker 1] Coming.
- [foreman] Mikey,

244
00:13:28,588 --> 00:13:30,087
hey, we're back in business.

245
00:13:30,088 --> 00:13:31,754
- Let's go.
- [Mikey] Yes, sir.

246
00:13:31,755 --> 00:13:32,962
[workers shouting indistinctly]

247
00:13:32,963 --> 00:13:35,047
[worker 2] There's too much traffic.
All right?

248
00:13:35,547 --> 00:13:38,004
- [worker 2] Hurry up.
- Yes. Filling a hole like this,

249
00:13:38,005 --> 00:13:39,796
it's not rocket science.

250
00:13:39,797 --> 00:13:42,254
Remember I told you
that I'd get things done?

251
00:13:42,255 --> 00:13:44,296
Well, here I am getting them done.

252
00:13:44,297 --> 00:13:46,255
- [man] Fuck yeah!
- [crowd cheering]

253
00:13:47,380 --> 00:13:48,379
[man 2] I love you, man.

254
00:13:48,380 --> 00:13:49,754
[cheering continues]

255
00:13:49,755 --> 00:13:52,005
[Fisk] I assume
that is what you meant by optics.

256
00:13:52,797 --> 00:13:55,587
Yes, Mayor Fisk. It was indeed.

257
00:13:55,588 --> 00:13:56,796
- [Daniel] Sir?
- [Fisk] Yeah.

258
00:13:56,797 --> 00:13:59,546
Solid hole work, you know,
filling in that hole.

259
00:13:59,547 --> 00:14:00,755
Oh, thank you, Daniel.

260
00:14:01,880 --> 00:14:04,421
[♪ intriguing music playing]

261
00:14:04,422 --> 00:14:07,671
[Kirsten] I send you off for a DUl,
and you come back with a cop killing?

262
00:14:07,672 --> 00:14:09,671
With everything that this firm
has going on right now?

263
00:14:09,672 --> 00:14:11,462
The cops at the station
were beating him senseless.

264
00:14:11,463 --> 00:14:12,546
What did you want me to do?

265
00:14:12,547 --> 00:14:14,130
He probably wouldn't have made it
past the weekend.

266
00:14:15,922 --> 00:14:17,587
And, for what it's worth,
I think he might be innocent.

267
00:14:17,588 --> 00:14:19,421
[Kirsten] You can barely handle
your current caseload.

268
00:14:19,422 --> 00:14:21,254
- I'd have to sit second chair.
- A high-profile case like this

269
00:14:21,255 --> 00:14:23,171
- is not the worst thing in the world.
- It's exactly the opposite

270
00:14:23,172 --> 00:14:24,379
of what this firm needs right now.

271
00:14:24,380 --> 00:14:27,962
Okay, so my old partner at Midtown
slipped me the police report.

272
00:14:27,963 --> 00:14:31,462
The other cop said there was no victim.
He said that it was an unprovoked attack.

273
00:14:31,463 --> 00:14:33,546
Uh-- well, our client says there was.

274
00:14:33,547 --> 00:14:35,297
"He said, he said."

275
00:14:35,963 --> 00:14:37,379
Matt, you take on this case,

276
00:14:37,380 --> 00:14:39,837
it's gonna look like
you're siding against the whole NYPD.

277
00:14:39,838 --> 00:14:42,963
Kirsten, what did I tell you to get you
to come over from the DA's office?

278
00:14:44,172 --> 00:14:46,171
You said that I was brilliant,
which is true.

279
00:14:46,172 --> 00:14:48,713
[chuckles] That is true. What else?

280
00:14:50,672 --> 00:14:52,212
You said we'd take on the hard cases.

281
00:14:52,213 --> 00:14:54,672
[Matt] And impossible odds work
is what we do here.

282
00:14:59,755 --> 00:15:01,422
[sighs]

283
00:15:04,672 --> 00:15:05,672
Okay.

284
00:15:06,172 --> 00:15:07,171
Thank you.

285
00:15:07,172 --> 00:15:09,754
I just need Arnie to take over for me
on the Rogers depo.

286
00:15:09,755 --> 00:15:11,213
Great. I appreciate it.

287
00:15:11,963 --> 00:15:12,962
[door closes]

288
00:15:12,963 --> 00:15:15,629
Talk to Hector's wife,
and I need you to find the witness

289
00:15:15,630 --> 00:15:17,255
that Hector saved on the platform.

290
00:15:21,130 --> 00:15:22,380
I believe him, Cherry.

291
00:15:24,297 --> 00:15:25,713
[smacks lips] Okay.

292
00:15:26,713 --> 00:15:28,379
So you want me to find the guy
on the platform?

293
00:15:28,380 --> 00:15:29,504
Yes.

294
00:15:29,505 --> 00:15:31,047
How much you want me to push?

295
00:15:31,630 --> 00:15:33,130
As much as you have to...

296
00:15:34,463 --> 00:15:36,130
and do some digging on Hector for me.

297
00:15:36,922 --> 00:15:39,296
There's something about his story
that doesn't track.

298
00:15:39,297 --> 00:15:42,296
Wait. He's innocent
or his story doesn't track?

299
00:15:42,297 --> 00:15:43,796
Uh... [laughs]

300
00:15:43,797 --> 00:15:44,921
Both.

301
00:15:44,922 --> 00:15:46,837
[♪ suspenseful music playing]

302
00:15:46,838 --> 00:15:49,004
[reporter] There he is. Mr. Murdock.
Mr. Murdock. Over here.

303
00:15:49,005 --> 00:15:50,962
Why are you representing a cop killer,
Mr. Murdock?

304
00:15:50,963 --> 00:15:52,671
- Are you anti-cop?
- My client is innocent,

305
00:15:52,672 --> 00:15:54,671
and we look forward to his day in court.
Thank you very much.

306
00:15:54,672 --> 00:15:56,504
What does the Ayala family say about this?

307
00:15:56,505 --> 00:15:57,796
- Thank you.
- That's all for now.

308
00:15:57,797 --> 00:15:59,796
[reporter 2] Are you worried
about the reputation of your firm?

309
00:15:59,797 --> 00:16:02,462
[reporter 3] How does it feel to know
that Mayor Fisk will watch this closely?

310
00:16:02,463 --> 00:16:04,088
[♪ suspenseful music continues]

311
00:16:05,838 --> 00:16:07,879
[chains clanking]

312
00:16:07,880 --> 00:16:09,338
[door opens]

313
00:16:17,338 --> 00:16:18,922
[cane clacking]

314
00:16:22,005 --> 00:16:24,588
Drakkar Noir, the scent of choice
for New York's finest.

315
00:16:25,922 --> 00:16:27,796
- [Kirsten] NYPD backs its own.
- [door opens]

316
00:16:27,797 --> 00:16:29,422
[indistinct whispering]

317
00:16:34,422 --> 00:16:36,505
[echoing] That's the asshole
who killed my partner.

318
00:16:37,922 --> 00:16:38,963
How you doing, Hector?

319
00:16:39,547 --> 00:16:41,087
- Pretty bad, Matt.
- All right. Hang in there.

320
00:16:41,088 --> 00:16:43,421
Like I said,
the first step in a long process.

321
00:16:43,422 --> 00:16:44,505
Is your wife here?

322
00:16:46,172 --> 00:16:47,171
[Hector] No.

323
00:16:47,172 --> 00:16:48,380
[door opens]

324
00:16:49,047 --> 00:16:50,047
[door closes]

325
00:16:51,797 --> 00:16:53,797
- Oh, shit.
- [Matt] What?

326
00:16:54,797 --> 00:16:55,880
It's the Hawk.

327
00:16:56,463 --> 00:16:57,504
Hochberg?

328
00:16:57,505 --> 00:16:59,130
- Mmm-hmm.
- [footsteps approaching]

329
00:17:01,005 --> 00:17:02,672
[gate squeaks]

330
00:17:04,005 --> 00:17:06,587
People of the state of New York
versus Hector Ayala

331
00:17:06,588 --> 00:17:08,921
Charged with murder in the first degree,
second degree,

332
00:17:08,922 --> 00:17:10,587
and manslaughter in the first degree.

333
00:17:10,588 --> 00:17:13,046
[Hochberg] Benjamin Hochberg, Your Honor,
representing the People

334
00:17:13,047 --> 00:17:15,754
- of the State of New York.
- Matt Murdock for the defense, Your Honor.

335
00:17:15,755 --> 00:17:19,129
- We'll waive the readings, not the rights.
- Given the serious nature of the charges,

336
00:17:19,130 --> 00:17:22,087
People ask that the defendant
be remanded without bail.

337
00:17:22,088 --> 00:17:25,047
- Your Honor, the defense would ask--
- The People's motion is granted.

338
00:17:25,838 --> 00:17:28,962
- Uh... Your Honor, if I could--
- I said bail is denied.

339
00:17:28,963 --> 00:17:30,129
[smacks lips]

340
00:17:30,130 --> 00:17:32,754
Mr. Ayala is a decorated Army veteran.
He has no record.

341
00:17:32,755 --> 00:17:35,504
He served as a CPA for 15 years.
He's a pillar of his community.

342
00:17:35,505 --> 00:17:38,546
He's also accused of killing
a New York City police officer.

343
00:17:38,547 --> 00:17:40,713
- Next case, please.
- Thank you, Your Honor.

344
00:17:42,838 --> 00:17:45,004
- In good hands, huh?
- It's gonna be okay.

345
00:17:45,005 --> 00:17:46,713
[indistinct chatter]

346
00:17:54,088 --> 00:17:55,088
[BB sighs]

347
00:17:55,672 --> 00:17:58,254
You know, I should have known
that you had an agenda,

348
00:17:58,255 --> 00:17:59,921
giving me your number the other night.

349
00:17:59,922 --> 00:18:01,297
[BB] I'm a journalist, bro.

350
00:18:02,547 --> 00:18:06,337
Besides, we can kill it here
as friends with political benefits.

351
00:18:06,338 --> 00:18:09,837
You get me access to him, I give him
a straight line to the under-30 demo.

352
00:18:09,838 --> 00:18:12,462
And then who's got two thumbs
and is a total hero?

353
00:18:12,463 --> 00:18:13,754
Me.

354
00:18:13,755 --> 00:18:15,338
- [chuckles]
- Phone.

355
00:18:16,005 --> 00:18:17,046
What? Bullshit.

356
00:18:17,047 --> 00:18:19,172
Condition of this level of access.

357
00:18:20,213 --> 00:18:23,297
I'm covering my ass. So you don't post.

358
00:18:25,047 --> 00:18:26,047
Fair enough.

359
00:18:28,130 --> 00:18:32,047
Look, play softball in there, okay?
I'm calling in a favor.

360
00:18:32,630 --> 00:18:34,380
Wait, I thought you said you were his guy.

361
00:18:35,005 --> 00:18:37,463
I am.
I might have embellished a little bit.

362
00:18:38,297 --> 00:18:39,297
[BB] Wow.

363
00:18:39,838 --> 00:18:43,004
You know, I can't tell
if you're an idiot or an operator.

364
00:18:43,005 --> 00:18:46,213
Well, maybe I'm... I don't know what I am.

365
00:18:49,672 --> 00:18:50,797
You've got five.

366
00:18:59,880 --> 00:19:04,004
I must say, your coverage
of my campaign was spot on.

367
00:19:04,005 --> 00:19:07,713
And not for nothing, you're one
of the first people to take me seriously.

368
00:19:09,422 --> 00:19:12,212
BB. Is that short for something?
Beatrice? Betty?

369
00:19:12,213 --> 00:19:15,213
Just BB. I was named for my uncle.

370
00:19:17,338 --> 00:19:18,338
Ben Urich.

371
00:19:19,172 --> 00:19:20,879
[♪ suspenseful music playing]

372
00:19:20,880 --> 00:19:21,963
Yeah.

373
00:19:22,963 --> 00:19:23,963
[Fisk] I knew him.

374
00:19:26,005 --> 00:19:27,921
He was a good journalist.

375
00:19:27,922 --> 00:19:30,047
[♪ suspenseful music continues]

376
00:19:34,755 --> 00:19:38,005
I asked Commissioner Gallo about you
on three separate occasions.

377
00:19:39,130 --> 00:19:40,130
Every time...

378
00:19:41,338 --> 00:19:42,338
nothing.

379
00:19:43,172 --> 00:19:44,462
Not a word.

380
00:19:44,463 --> 00:19:45,838
It's got me thinking.

381
00:19:47,422 --> 00:19:49,005
There must be a story there.

382
00:19:50,672 --> 00:19:51,672
And is there?

383
00:19:52,213 --> 00:19:53,421
[smacks lips]

384
00:19:53,422 --> 00:19:56,963
One of my sources at the NYPD tells me
that Gallo is now poised to resign.

385
00:19:57,838 --> 00:20:00,046
I mean, Gallo is a celebrated
police commissioner.

386
00:20:00,047 --> 00:20:02,588
Maybe the most beloved
this city has ever seen.

387
00:20:03,088 --> 00:20:05,630
That puts you in a big fat bind.

388
00:20:06,297 --> 00:20:09,379
That NYPD's rank and file are planning
on standing behind their guy

389
00:20:09,380 --> 00:20:11,212
in protest of you, Mr. Mayor.

390
00:20:11,213 --> 00:20:13,921
I mean, the force
is already woefully understaffed,

391
00:20:13,922 --> 00:20:16,296
and you've got vigilantes
picking up the slack.

392
00:20:16,297 --> 00:20:18,297
[♪ music intensifies]

393
00:20:20,130 --> 00:20:23,297
If you lose the cops, you lose the city.

394
00:20:25,588 --> 00:20:26,754
Thank you, Ms. Urich.

395
00:20:26,755 --> 00:20:28,463
[paper rustling]

396
00:20:31,172 --> 00:20:33,713
Just one more question about Mrs. Fisk.

397
00:20:35,422 --> 00:20:37,380
I'm sorry, but I'm out of time.

398
00:20:38,005 --> 00:20:39,213
[Buck] This way, please.

399
00:20:46,338 --> 00:20:48,422
- [door opens]
- Thank you, Mr. Mayor. I...

400
00:20:49,463 --> 00:20:50,963
I hope we speak again soon.

401
00:20:56,422 --> 00:20:57,712
[door closes]

402
00:20:57,713 --> 00:21:01,796
Sir, I am so sorry. She was not supposed
to ask about your wife. I--

403
00:21:01,797 --> 00:21:03,130
It's okay, Daniel.

404
00:21:04,172 --> 00:21:09,213
I have a feeling that this young woman
is used to being underestimated.

405
00:21:11,588 --> 00:21:12,713
We'll use that.

406
00:21:15,838 --> 00:21:19,879
Confronting one's past trauma
can lead to building skills

407
00:21:19,880 --> 00:21:22,922
and techniques to find peace.
Like the book says,

408
00:21:23,713 --> 00:21:26,838
"Identify, interrogate, release."

409
00:21:27,505 --> 00:21:30,005
So, any hints about your next book?

410
00:21:30,922 --> 00:21:33,380
I've been thinking a lot
about projected personas.

411
00:21:33,922 --> 00:21:36,629
How we present a curated version
of ourselves,

412
00:21:36,630 --> 00:21:41,297
like through filters on social media
or masks.

413
00:21:41,838 --> 00:21:45,422
[moderator] Mmm. Interesting.
[chuckles] Maybe even timely.

414
00:21:46,047 --> 00:21:48,879
Could be. It's still in the early stages,

415
00:21:48,880 --> 00:21:51,587
but, um, I'll make sure
to give you a galley copy.

416
00:21:51,588 --> 00:21:54,629
Thank you. And thanks for coming today.

417
00:21:54,630 --> 00:21:56,005
You're very welcome.

418
00:21:58,588 --> 00:22:00,213
[♪ soft pop music playing]

419
00:22:02,797 --> 00:22:05,422
[Heather] Thank you so much for coming.
I really appreciate it.

420
00:22:08,005 --> 00:22:09,713
I-- I love your work.

421
00:22:10,422 --> 00:22:11,422
Thank you.

422
00:22:12,088 --> 00:22:14,212
- [inhales sharply]
- [indistinct chatter]

423
00:22:14,213 --> 00:22:16,297
Dr. Glenn, I need... I need help.

424
00:22:17,797 --> 00:22:20,630
Are you... Are you taking any new clients?

425
00:22:24,213 --> 00:22:28,005
[stutters] I can always
move things around. Here's my email.

426
00:22:30,255 --> 00:22:32,171
I'm sure we can work something out.

427
00:22:32,172 --> 00:22:34,338
Thank you. Truly.

428
00:22:39,380 --> 00:22:40,380
[man] Could you?

429
00:22:40,880 --> 00:22:41,880
Of course.

430
00:22:45,047 --> 00:22:46,797
[♪ ominous music playing]

431
00:22:49,672 --> 00:22:50,672
Thank you.

432
00:22:52,463 --> 00:22:53,463
No, thank you.

433
00:22:55,713 --> 00:22:57,963
[bagpipes playing]

434
00:23:02,922 --> 00:23:05,212
Quite beautiful.
Really, thank you very much.

435
00:23:05,213 --> 00:23:07,754
Thanks, guys, all right? We'll see you.

436
00:23:07,755 --> 00:23:09,672
[♪ haunting music playing]

437
00:23:18,463 --> 00:23:20,255
Honey, I gotta go deal with this.

438
00:23:31,463 --> 00:23:34,838
It's a classy move, turning up
to a police funeral after it's ended.

439
00:23:35,672 --> 00:23:39,297
I didn't want to distract
from the ceremony, Commissioner.

440
00:23:40,672 --> 00:23:42,213
I did need to talk to you.

441
00:23:42,922 --> 00:23:46,463
I wonder how it feels for a guy like you
to come to a place like this.

442
00:23:47,213 --> 00:23:49,963
Are you even capable
of feeling guilt or remorse?

443
00:23:50,672 --> 00:23:51,672
Guilt?

444
00:23:53,213 --> 00:23:55,129
I didn't kill Officer Shanahan.

445
00:23:55,130 --> 00:23:57,380
Maybe not him, but plenty of others.

446
00:23:58,047 --> 00:24:03,172
[scoffs] Still makes no sense to me,
this mayor thing.

447
00:24:04,505 --> 00:24:06,796
So you gave up
your criminal empire for what?

448
00:24:06,797 --> 00:24:10,130
So you could have less money
and less power?

449
00:24:11,047 --> 00:24:13,922
So you could kowtow to an Italian
son of a bitch in a cemetery?

450
00:24:17,838 --> 00:24:20,755
How are we gonna fix this issue?

451
00:24:21,838 --> 00:24:23,797
Do you...
Do you know who Samuel Vance was?

452
00:24:24,505 --> 00:24:25,629
No, of course you don't.

453
00:24:25,630 --> 00:24:30,338
Mayor Vance was the mayor of New York
in 1874. He served for one month.

454
00:24:31,213 --> 00:24:35,255
It is my personal mission to make sure
that your term is shorter than his.

455
00:24:36,172 --> 00:24:37,796
[♪ unsettling music playing]

456
00:24:37,797 --> 00:24:39,629
I see right through you, Fisk.

457
00:24:39,630 --> 00:24:44,047
You... You're not a mayor
who loves his city. You're a whiny kid

458
00:24:44,922 --> 00:24:46,713
who wants everyone to love him,

459
00:24:47,505 --> 00:24:49,797
a monster trying to rewrite his legacy.

460
00:24:51,047 --> 00:24:52,088
Well, guess what?

461
00:24:53,755 --> 00:24:54,755
It's too late.

462
00:24:55,463 --> 00:24:57,297
Once a thug, always a thug.

463
00:25:00,047 --> 00:25:01,672
See you around, Kingpin.

464
00:25:02,672 --> 00:25:04,672
[♪ unsettling music continues]

465
00:25:09,588 --> 00:25:11,379
[cars honking]

466
00:25:11,380 --> 00:25:13,088
[indistinct chatter]

467
00:25:15,380 --> 00:25:19,380
[Kirsten] Your husband needs you, Soledad.
It's important that you're seen in court.

468
00:25:20,338 --> 00:25:21,671
Can I ask you both something?

469
00:25:21,672 --> 00:25:25,087
We've read the papers,
seen the news and all that.

470
00:25:25,088 --> 00:25:26,255
Can you just be straight?

471
00:25:26,880 --> 00:25:28,422
Does my husband have a chance?

472
00:25:29,213 --> 00:25:31,046
[Cherry] An NYPD cop is dead.

473
00:25:31,047 --> 00:25:33,837
And anytime that happens,
a big machine gets turned on

474
00:25:33,838 --> 00:25:37,380
to try to figure out what went wrong.
And to punish whoever killed the cop.

475
00:25:38,338 --> 00:25:41,630
Punish them severely.
And that machine has no off switch.

476
00:25:42,463 --> 00:25:44,547
It just goes and goes until somebody pays.

477
00:25:45,130 --> 00:25:48,421
But Matt Murdock and this woman here

478
00:25:48,422 --> 00:25:51,379
are the two best lawyers
I've ever seen, so.

479
00:25:51,380 --> 00:25:53,880
Now, if I could just get
Hector's suit for court?

480
00:25:55,588 --> 00:25:57,462
Okay, it's on the bed.
I can get it together.

481
00:25:57,463 --> 00:25:59,088
No, no, no, no. You two stay and talk.

482
00:26:05,588 --> 00:26:08,630
Soledad, whatever is going on
between you and Hector,

483
00:26:09,380 --> 00:26:12,587
I'm really hoping you can set it aside.
He needs you.

484
00:26:12,588 --> 00:26:14,713
He needs me,
or he needs me to show up in court?

485
00:26:16,505 --> 00:26:18,713
[Kirsten] Trials are about feelings
as much as facts.

486
00:26:20,005 --> 00:26:23,504
The jury is gonna feel a certain way
if you're there by his side

487
00:26:23,505 --> 00:26:25,587
and another if you're absent.

488
00:26:25,588 --> 00:26:27,379
[♪ slow suspenseful music playing]

489
00:26:27,380 --> 00:26:28,547
[Soledad] I need to get to work.

490
00:26:31,880 --> 00:26:32,880
Are you married?

491
00:26:34,172 --> 00:26:35,172
No, I'm not.

492
00:26:36,213 --> 00:26:37,880
[Soledad] When you first come together,

493
00:26:38,505 --> 00:26:42,630
everything feels wide open.
Anything's possible.

494
00:26:43,255 --> 00:26:47,129
- Little by little, that fades.
- [bottle cap squeaks, clatters]

495
00:26:47,130 --> 00:26:48,547
Things changed.

496
00:26:49,130 --> 00:26:51,547
Hector... he's not the man I married.

497
00:26:52,547 --> 00:26:54,504
[♪ tense music playing]

498
00:26:54,505 --> 00:26:56,921
[Kirsten] This all boils down
to one question.

499
00:26:56,922 --> 00:26:59,463
Do you want this man
spending his life in prison?

500
00:27:01,255 --> 00:27:02,629
[Matt] You're taking me to Eastern Europe?

501
00:27:02,630 --> 00:27:04,379
- [Heather] Yes.
- [Matt] It's fine with me.

502
00:27:04,380 --> 00:27:05,504
How about...

503
00:27:05,505 --> 00:27:07,005
- [♪ upbeat music playing]
- [Heather] Mmm...

504
00:27:07,922 --> 00:27:10,963
Belize? Belize I like.

505
00:27:11,672 --> 00:27:15,087
The jewel in the heart
of the Caribbean Basin.

506
00:27:15,088 --> 00:27:17,129
- Perfect. Yep.
- [Heather] Salty sea air...

507
00:27:17,130 --> 00:27:18,754
Warm sand between our toes.

508
00:27:18,755 --> 00:27:21,630
- Double-fisting mai tais.
- [Matt chuckles]

509
00:27:22,297 --> 00:27:26,713
Yeah, that sounds good.
Okay, so this fantasy of ours...

510
00:27:28,213 --> 00:27:30,212
What happens after the mai tais?

511
00:27:30,213 --> 00:27:33,254
Oh, um, the possibilities are endless.

512
00:27:33,255 --> 00:27:35,046
- [Matt] Oh, yeah?
- Mmm-hmm.

513
00:27:35,047 --> 00:27:38,504
Maybe, uh, later, I can give you a taste.

514
00:27:38,505 --> 00:27:39,796
We'll take the check, please?

515
00:27:39,797 --> 00:27:42,296
- [chuckles]
- [cell phone vibrating]

516
00:27:42,297 --> 00:27:43,422
Sorry.

517
00:27:44,172 --> 00:27:45,171
[automated voice] <i>Cherry Mobile.</i>

518
00:27:45,172 --> 00:27:47,587
Do you mind? I-- I don't think he'd call
unless it was important.

519
00:27:47,588 --> 00:27:48,962
- Take it.
- Yeah. It'll be two seconds.

520
00:27:48,963 --> 00:27:50,213
You'll make it up to me later.

521
00:27:50,672 --> 00:27:53,296
- With interest, I promise. [chuckles]
- [Heather] I'll collect.

522
00:27:53,297 --> 00:27:55,837
- Cherry, talk to me.
- [Cherry] <i>Guess what I found.</i>

523
00:27:55,838 --> 00:27:58,172
[♪ dramatic music playing]

524
00:28:03,047 --> 00:28:04,630
[♪ ominous music playing]

525
00:28:09,505 --> 00:28:11,712
[Matt] White Tiger? Really?

526
00:28:11,713 --> 00:28:13,171
You were investigating me?

527
00:28:13,172 --> 00:28:15,171
We talked for hours
and you neglect to tell me

528
00:28:15,172 --> 00:28:16,629
that you moonlight as a vigilante?

529
00:28:16,630 --> 00:28:19,796
I wasn't in the suit or wearing my amulet.

530
00:28:19,797 --> 00:28:21,921
I had no extra powers. It's not relevant.

531
00:28:21,922 --> 00:28:23,297
It's relevant.

532
00:28:24,463 --> 00:28:27,629
You hide your identity and go out
and solve things the way you see fit.

533
00:28:27,630 --> 00:28:29,587
We're trying to position this
as a one-off event.

534
00:28:29,588 --> 00:28:31,421
I find out you're going out at night
looking for trouble.

535
00:28:31,422 --> 00:28:32,922
I'm not looking for trouble.

536
00:28:34,755 --> 00:28:36,297
Someone's gotta protect the streets.

537
00:28:37,005 --> 00:28:39,005
People are going missing.
No one seems to care.

538
00:28:39,880 --> 00:28:41,671
It's not like Daredevil's around anymore.

539
00:28:41,672 --> 00:28:42,797
[chuckles]

540
00:28:44,255 --> 00:28:45,379
[sighs]

541
00:28:45,380 --> 00:28:48,630
If I can find this out,
you better believe the DA's office can.

542
00:28:49,213 --> 00:28:52,130
Let them. The people need a hero.

543
00:28:53,255 --> 00:28:56,296
I'm out there every night,
putting my life on the line for them.

544
00:28:56,297 --> 00:28:58,255
Your wife agree with that choice?

545
00:29:01,047 --> 00:29:02,547
This is a tough case, Hector.

546
00:29:03,297 --> 00:29:04,547
A cop is dead.

547
00:29:05,088 --> 00:29:07,922
And the only way I can win it
is if I know every way I can lose it.

548
00:29:11,047 --> 00:29:12,047
You're right.

549
00:29:13,005 --> 00:29:14,879
You're right. I'm sorry.
I should have told you.

550
00:29:14,880 --> 00:29:16,671
[Hector sniffles, groans]

551
00:29:16,672 --> 00:29:19,296
You okay? Sound like you're in pain.

552
00:29:19,297 --> 00:29:22,129
Hmm. [sighs wearily]

553
00:29:22,130 --> 00:29:24,005
Rikers Island is no picnic.

554
00:29:24,963 --> 00:29:28,755
It's equal opportunity beatdowns.
Guards and inmates alike.

555
00:29:29,422 --> 00:29:32,172
All right, hang in there, okay?
I'll make some calls, see what I can do.

556
00:29:36,380 --> 00:29:37,672
[Buck] He's been waiting 20 minutes.

557
00:29:38,797 --> 00:29:40,588
Yes. Yeah. Send him in.

558
00:29:43,838 --> 00:29:45,171
[Gallo] Well, you seem pretty busy,

559
00:29:45,172 --> 00:29:47,047
so I'll get right to the point.

560
00:29:47,630 --> 00:29:51,879
I'm resigning my post,
effective tonight at midnight.

561
00:29:51,880 --> 00:29:53,712
And due to unforeseen
scheduling conflicts,

562
00:29:53,713 --> 00:29:57,005
I will not be able to stay on
to help with the transition.

563
00:29:57,463 --> 00:29:59,754
But you will need a new
Police Commissioner,

564
00:29:59,755 --> 00:30:03,380
and-- [chuckles] And guess what?
A lot of new cops as well.

565
00:30:05,255 --> 00:30:06,255
Goodbye, Fisk.

566
00:30:07,005 --> 00:30:08,713
[Fisk] Before you go, just one thing.

567
00:30:13,505 --> 00:30:16,755
You're originally from Philadelphia.

568
00:30:17,213 --> 00:30:18,963
- That's right.
- And you know that,

569
00:30:19,797 --> 00:30:22,296
the cheesesteaks are great in Philly.

570
00:30:22,297 --> 00:30:25,046
Mr. Cashman, what's the name
of the one that we like?

571
00:30:25,047 --> 00:30:26,379
Geno's, Mr. Mayor.

572
00:30:26,380 --> 00:30:29,087
Geno's, right, right.
But that's your favorite.

573
00:30:29,088 --> 00:30:30,422
I... I...

574
00:30:31,213 --> 00:30:35,880
I think that the best is one that I found.
It's actually right outside of the city.

575
00:30:38,672 --> 00:30:40,712
D'Angelo's in King of Prussia.

576
00:30:40,713 --> 00:30:41,796
[♪ menacing music playing]

577
00:30:41,797 --> 00:30:46,172
Mr. Cashman was kind enough to drive down
there and pick me one up for lunch.

578
00:30:46,672 --> 00:30:48,588
It was delicious.

579
00:30:50,963 --> 00:30:53,255
The concept of compromise...

580
00:30:54,547 --> 00:30:56,755
it's been on my mind a lot.

581
00:30:58,255 --> 00:31:02,338
So I have some compromises to propose.

582
00:31:05,297 --> 00:31:09,880
As far as a pay raise
for your police force,

583
00:31:11,088 --> 00:31:12,088
zero.

584
00:31:13,755 --> 00:31:18,255
And when it comes to overtime minimums...

585
00:31:21,422 --> 00:31:22,422
None.

586
00:31:24,047 --> 00:31:26,046
And... and...

587
00:31:26,047 --> 00:31:29,172
- An expanded cadet class.
- Yes, yes.

588
00:31:29,922 --> 00:31:31,255
That's not happening.

589
00:31:32,172 --> 00:31:35,130
So what do you say, Commissioner?
Do we have a deal?

590
00:31:40,172 --> 00:31:42,672
Fine. No, I'll stay.

591
00:31:45,088 --> 00:31:46,963
Be careful what you wish for.

592
00:31:50,547 --> 00:31:52,755
- [door opens]
- Well played.

593
00:31:54,130 --> 00:31:55,130
No.

594
00:31:56,797 --> 00:31:58,588
For the most part, men are weak.

595
00:32:00,047 --> 00:32:04,630
Any man can be swayed
by a single piece of paper.

596
00:32:06,047 --> 00:32:08,630
He thought he could keep
that child a secret.

597
00:32:10,838 --> 00:32:12,963
Sandwich was disgusting.

598
00:32:14,005 --> 00:32:16,587
Hector's history as the White Tiger
has no bearing on this case.

599
00:32:16,588 --> 00:32:18,087
The defense moves to suppress.

600
00:32:18,088 --> 00:32:20,879
[scoffs] This is next level, Murdock.
That guy's a vigilante.

601
00:32:20,880 --> 00:32:22,587
Who wasn't in possession
of his mystical amulet.

602
00:32:22,588 --> 00:32:24,754
Or in the White Tiger outfit
at the time of the incident.

603
00:32:24,755 --> 00:32:28,879
Allowing this type of totally inflammatory
information will unfairly bias the jurors.

604
00:32:28,880 --> 00:32:31,962
It perfectly meets the standard
of more prejudicial than probative.

605
00:32:31,963 --> 00:32:34,712
Cut the crap. It speaks straight
to the heart of the case.

606
00:32:34,713 --> 00:32:36,712
It suggests a pattern of behavior

607
00:32:36,713 --> 00:32:38,546
- that drove Hector Ayala...
- [Matt scoffs] Please.

608
00:32:38,547 --> 00:32:39,712
...to kill Officer Shanahan

609
00:32:39,713 --> 00:32:41,879
- on that subway platform.
- Your Honor, the jury will be

610
00:32:41,880 --> 00:32:44,171
deliberating about the tragic events
of a single evening.

611
00:32:44,172 --> 00:32:46,463
The proceedings must rest
not on my client's clothing,

612
00:32:47,005 --> 00:32:49,213
but what happened on the platform
that night.

613
00:32:51,672 --> 00:32:52,672
[sighs]

614
00:32:53,255 --> 00:32:55,629
Look... [chuckles] I get... I get it.
I do. I get the instinct

615
00:32:55,630 --> 00:32:57,462
to allow everything
but the kitchen sink in as evidence.

616
00:32:57,463 --> 00:33:01,796
But it's not right, and with respect,
it's not what you're up there to do.

617
00:33:01,797 --> 00:33:03,172
[judge chuckles]

618
00:33:08,380 --> 00:33:09,546
- Okay.
- Oh, my God.

619
00:33:09,547 --> 00:33:11,254
I'm granting the motion <i>in limine.</i>

620
00:33:11,255 --> 00:33:14,046
The People are directed not to discuss
or introduce any evidence

621
00:33:14,047 --> 00:33:15,879
of Hector Ayala's life as White Tiger

622
00:33:15,880 --> 00:33:17,337
- or any acts of vigilantism.
- [Hochberg scoffs]

623
00:33:17,338 --> 00:33:19,004
This is some bullshit, Jerry.

624
00:33:19,005 --> 00:33:20,087
Thank you, Your Honor.

625
00:33:20,088 --> 00:33:22,463
[man] <i>When I was comin' up
and you seen the blue,</i>

626
00:33:22,922 --> 00:33:24,380
{\an8}you looked at those brass buttons.

627
00:33:25,130 --> 00:33:27,462
{\an8}It says something,
it meant something, you know?

628
00:33:27,463 --> 00:33:29,713
{\an8}<i>But there's none of that.
There's no respect anymore.</i>

629
00:33:32,005 --> 00:33:36,046
{\an8}[woman] <i>Jails are revolving doors now.
Police officers have their hands tied.</i>

630
00:33:36,047 --> 00:33:39,087
{\an8}I feel like nobody's
being held accountable,

631
00:33:39,088 --> 00:33:43,379
{\an8}and I'm sick and tired of being afraid.

632
00:33:43,380 --> 00:33:45,129
[ship horn blaring]

633
00:33:45,130 --> 00:33:46,880
[waves lapping]

634
00:33:51,505 --> 00:33:53,255
[seagulls squawking]

635
00:34:00,463 --> 00:34:01,588
Find the witness?

636
00:34:02,172 --> 00:34:04,130
Ghosts are hard to find, Matty.

637
00:34:04,797 --> 00:34:07,047
- Isn't that why I hired you?
- [chuckles]

638
00:34:07,797 --> 00:34:10,630
My ghost bustin' days
are long gone, my friend.

639
00:34:11,213 --> 00:34:14,713
We're just not finding anything
that says the guy is telling the truth.

640
00:34:15,963 --> 00:34:17,547
[Matt] Except for the fact that he is.

641
00:34:19,213 --> 00:34:23,962
I know this case hits close to home.
All the more reason it's dangerous.

642
00:34:23,963 --> 00:34:25,047
[Matt chuckles]

643
00:34:26,380 --> 00:34:29,130
Are you saying my judgment is clouded
because of who Hector is?

644
00:34:30,463 --> 00:34:32,713
'Cause of who you are.

645
00:34:33,297 --> 00:34:34,838
- 'Cause of who you were.
- Nah.

646
00:34:35,380 --> 00:34:38,838
- This case is about Hector Ayala.
- Okay.

647
00:34:39,630 --> 00:34:42,629
Let's say you're right and I'm wrong.
Hypothetically speaking--

648
00:34:42,630 --> 00:34:45,255
It's not hypothetical, Cherry, is it?

649
00:34:46,213 --> 00:34:48,171
- Is it?
- [sighs]

650
00:34:48,172 --> 00:34:50,379
You know I know he was telling the truth.

651
00:34:50,380 --> 00:34:53,130
And we both know it doesn't matter
if you can't prove it.

652
00:34:54,297 --> 00:34:55,505
And for what it's worth,

653
00:34:56,130 --> 00:34:58,713
I like the Matt Murdock
I've seen this year.

654
00:34:59,255 --> 00:35:01,462
The guy that went out
and found his own way,

655
00:35:01,463 --> 00:35:03,172
got out of the Kitchen, wears a...

656
00:35:04,338 --> 00:35:06,546
normal suit. He's doing some good.

657
00:35:06,547 --> 00:35:08,838
[♪ somber music playing]

658
00:35:15,880 --> 00:35:17,963
[♪ somber music continues]

659
00:35:26,088 --> 00:35:27,755
[indistinct conversation]

660
00:35:41,088 --> 00:35:42,712
[pastor echoing] "Behold the Lamb of God.

661
00:35:42,713 --> 00:35:45,879
"Behold him who takes away
the sins of the world.

662
00:35:45,880 --> 00:35:48,797
"Blessed are those called
to the supper of the Lamb."

663
00:35:49,380 --> 00:35:52,879
[congregation] "Lord, I am not worthy
that you should enter under my roof,

664
00:35:52,880 --> 00:35:56,213
"but only say the word
and my soul shall be healed."

665
00:35:57,088 --> 00:35:59,130
[♪ dramatic music playing]

666
00:36:02,297 --> 00:36:05,546
Um, finally finished all my paperwork.
[echoes] That's it for me.

667
00:36:05,547 --> 00:36:06,963
[dog barking]

668
00:36:07,880 --> 00:36:09,797
- [cars honking]
- [metal rattling]

669
00:36:12,297 --> 00:36:14,754
- [Powell] I'm headed home.
- [footsteps echoing]

670
00:36:14,755 --> 00:36:16,880
[cars honking]

671
00:36:18,380 --> 00:36:20,172
[♪ music intensifies]

672
00:36:22,463 --> 00:36:24,297
[choir vocalizing]

673
00:36:47,297 --> 00:36:49,130
[♪ dramatic music continues]

674
00:36:54,005 --> 00:36:56,047
- [taxi honking]
- [tires screeching]

675
00:36:59,755 --> 00:37:01,797
[♪ dramatic music continues]

676
00:37:15,797 --> 00:37:17,547
[♪ music intensifies]

677
00:37:20,755 --> 00:37:23,421
- [door closes]
- [cell phone vibrating]

678
00:37:23,422 --> 00:37:24,587
[automated voice] <i>Heather calling.</i>

679
00:37:24,588 --> 00:37:26,172
[people talking indistinctly]

680
00:37:27,713 --> 00:37:29,379
- Hey.
- [Heather] <i>Hey. Um...</i>

681
00:37:29,380 --> 00:37:32,712
I won't be able to make our reservation
tonight. I'm meeting a new client.

682
00:37:32,713 --> 00:37:33,880
<i>Rain check?</i>

683
00:37:34,338 --> 00:37:35,630
- [can pops]
- [metal clinks]

684
00:37:37,338 --> 00:37:38,754
[commentator over TV]
<i>Just a missed opportunity.</i>

685
00:37:38,755 --> 00:37:40,004
Yeah, sounds good.

686
00:37:40,005 --> 00:37:41,172
Thanks.

687
00:37:43,380 --> 00:37:44,505
[sighs]

688
00:37:46,630 --> 00:37:49,172
These aren't really necessary.
It comes with the office.

689
00:37:53,047 --> 00:37:54,880
We appreciate your discretion.

690
00:37:58,588 --> 00:38:00,172
[♪ dramatic choral music playing]

691
00:38:01,088 --> 00:38:02,922
[Buck] Sir? Madam.

692
00:38:06,505 --> 00:38:10,588
Dr. Glenn, allow me to introduce
Mayor and Mrs. Fisk.

693
00:38:16,088 --> 00:38:19,005
[Heather] So I usually like to start off
with a couple of questions.

694
00:38:20,213 --> 00:38:23,880
What sparked you to come to therapy,
and what would you like to get out of it?

695
00:38:26,755 --> 00:38:29,213
Vanessa, why don't you start us off?

696
00:38:32,047 --> 00:38:36,547
My husband and I have been through
a lot these last couple of years.

697
00:38:39,338 --> 00:38:40,712
[chuckles dryly]

698
00:38:40,713 --> 00:38:43,880
Until very recently,
we ran a complex business.

699
00:38:44,630 --> 00:38:46,880
Then Wilson left.

700
00:38:49,047 --> 00:38:50,588
Disappeared, really. [chuckles]

701
00:38:52,547 --> 00:38:54,797
[Heather] I'm curious to hear
more about that.

702
00:38:56,047 --> 00:38:57,047
Wilson?

703
00:39:00,130 --> 00:39:02,213
I was assaulted by a vigilante.

704
00:39:04,630 --> 00:39:08,213
The... recovery process,
it was quite involved.

705
00:39:12,047 --> 00:39:14,129
I couldn't stay in touch with Vanessa.

706
00:39:14,130 --> 00:39:16,338
I couldn't stay in communication with her.

707
00:39:16,880 --> 00:39:18,005
It was for the best.

708
00:39:19,255 --> 00:39:21,213
Was it for the best for you, Vanessa?

709
00:39:22,547 --> 00:39:24,505
- I think in some ways, it was--
- In some ways--

710
00:39:30,130 --> 00:39:31,755
I... I took over the business.

711
00:39:32,755 --> 00:39:33,755
It thrived.

712
00:39:35,172 --> 00:39:37,547
It had never been more profitable.

713
00:39:38,380 --> 00:39:42,172
And relationship between
management and labor was...

714
00:39:43,672 --> 00:39:45,713
robust. And fulfilling.

715
00:39:46,630 --> 00:39:47,713
For both sides.

716
00:39:48,963 --> 00:39:51,963
But was your husband's absence
fulfilling for you personally?

717
00:39:53,505 --> 00:39:55,212
[♪ melancholy music playing]

718
00:39:55,213 --> 00:39:56,297
I... uh...

719
00:39:59,547 --> 00:40:00,630
I was lonely.

720
00:40:03,838 --> 00:40:06,547
I missed Wilson.

721
00:40:07,963 --> 00:40:09,047
[smacks lips]

722
00:40:11,088 --> 00:40:15,172
Then he returns and I really don't know
how I feel about that.

723
00:40:18,297 --> 00:40:19,462
[breathes deeply]

724
00:40:19,463 --> 00:40:21,338
Why are we here?

725
00:40:25,255 --> 00:40:27,172
'Cause it doesn't feel like
we have a choice.

726
00:40:30,297 --> 00:40:32,005
I'd like to hear from you, Wilson.

727
00:40:35,922 --> 00:40:38,213
